-- Rebar Rises for First Time in Three Days on China Capacity Cuts
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-10-17T02:44:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-17/rebar-rises-for-first-time-in-three-days-on-china-capacity-cuts.html
Steel reinforcement-bar futures in
 Shanghai  rose for the first time in three days as China said it
would cut steel capacity.  Rebar for delivery in January on the Shanghai Futures
Exchange gained as much as 0.5 percent to 3,586  yuan  ($588) a
metric ton, before trading at 3,569 yuan at 10:42 a.m. local
time. The most-active contract closed at the lowest level in
more than three months yesterday.  China reiterated yesterday that 48 million tons of iron and
steel making capacity elimination is to be realized in 2014,
according to a statement by the State Council.  “China’s guidance expresses the government’s strong
determination and resolution in eliminating excess capacity and
restoring profitability in the  steel industry ,” said Xia
Caijun, an analyst at GF Futures Co. in Guangzhou.  The  spot price  of rebar fell by 0.2 percent to 3,512 yuan a
ton yesterday, according to Beijing Antaike Information
Development Co.  Iron ore  for immediate delivery at Tianjin port was little
changed yesterday at $133.70 a dry ton, according to a  price
index  compiled by The Steel Index Ltd.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
